However, it's worth noting that using try-with-resources for reading from the console input might cause issues if you have multiple read statements since the System.in resource will be closed after each statement.

A better solution would be to create a static Scanner object at the class level and use this object throughout the Keyboard class. Remember to close the Scanner object when the application ends. Here's the updated Keyboard.java class:

```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Keyboard {
    private static Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

    public static String readString(String prompt) {
        System.out.print(prompt);
        return scanner.nextLine();
    }

    // ... Other methods from the original Keyboard class ...

    public static void closeScanner() {
        scanner.close();
    }
}
```

