There isn't a specific DB2 table that contains the COBOL programs compilation date. However, you can usually find the compilation date and other source program information in the load module of the COBOL program. This information is stored in the object deck during the compile process and later linked in the load module.

To find the compilation date of a COBOL program, you can use the AMBLIST utility to analyze and produce a report of the load module. It will display information about the load module, including its source program information such as the compilation date, version, and more.

To run the AMBLIST utility, create a JCL with the following sample steps:

```
//your-job-name JOB ACCOUNT-INFO
//STEP1    EXEC PGM=AMBLIST
//SYSPRINT DD SYSOUT=*
//SYSUT1   DD DISP=SHR,DSN=load.library.name(member-name)
//SYSIN    DD *
  LISTIDR
/*
```

In this JCL, replace the `load.library.name(member-name)` with the actual library and member name of your COBOL load module. The output will contain information about the module, including the compilation date.

Keep in mind that the load module library and member names must be available and authorized for you to access them.

